    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my fiddle leaf fig looks like it's struggling and the roots are kind of circling the bottom of the pot. i think it's root bound. what kind of soil should i get for it and how do i repot it without killing it? it's super sensitive to change.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right to be concerned, but don't panic, because a fiddle leaf fig is a very stubborn and resilient plant that can handle a little stress if you move it carefully. First, let's get the soil right, because a fiddle leaf fig loves a heavy, well-draining mix that is almost like a solid brick to keep its roots from getting stuck. You want something like a 50/50 blend of potting soil and perlite or orchid bark, maybe even a little bit of coarse sand to help the roots breathe.\n\nNow, regarding the root circling, that is a classic sign of root-bound, but you can fix it without killing the plant by gently loosening the soil around the roots before you move it. Gently shake the pot to loosen the bottom layer, then use your fingers to carefully tease apart the circling roots, being very gentle so you don't snap them. Once you've loosened them, you can repot it into a slightly larger pot with fresh soil, making sure the new pot is only about an inch or two larger than the old one to avoid shocking the plant.\n\nAs for the soil, you want to get a mix that is heavy and well",
