      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the tips. so for the soil, i'm thinking of getting some peat moss too. is it better to keep the soil really dense so it stays moist, or should it be more loose? also, i'm a bit worried about the roots when i pull them out of the pot, they look a bit tangled and messy. any specific way to handle them so i don't damage the main root system?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to consider peat moss, but for a fiddle leaf fig, you should probably skip it and stick to that heavy, brick-like mix I mentioned earlier. Peat moss is too fluffy and airy; it will hold too much water and cause the roots to rot, which is exactly what you want to avoid. You want a soil that is dense enough to hold moisture but loose enough to let the roots breathe and move freely.\n\nRegarding the tangled roots, do not panic, but do not try to pull them out by hand either, as that will snap the delicate root hairs and cause shock. Instead, use your fingers to gently tease the soil apart while the plant is still in the pot, or use a small, soft brush to loosen the bottom layer. Once the soil is loose, you can carefully lift the entire plant out of the pot, supporting the stem with your other hand, and then gently separate the circling roots with your fingers.\n\nIf you are worried about the mess, try to keep the soil moist but not soggy, as this makes the roots easier to handle without snapping. Gently shake the pot over a trash can to dislodge excess soil, then use your fingers to carefully tease the",
