      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to be cautious, but you cannot see the root system without disturbing the soil, and that disturbance is exactly what you need to do to save the plant. The \"blind\" approach is actually the safest one for a fiddle leaf fig because the roots are often hidden deep within the dense, heavy soil mix you want to keep. If you try to dig or poke around blindly, you risk snapping those tiny, delicate root hairs that are essential for the plant's survival.\n\nInstead of trying to see what's going on, you should focus on the soil's texture and the plant's overall health before you even touch the roots. If the soil feels like a solid brick and the plant is drooping, that is a clear signal that it is root-bound, regardless of whether you can see the roots. The best way to handle the mess is to gently loosen the bottom layer of soil with your fingers or a soft brush, then carefully lift the entire pot out.\n\nOnce the plant is out, the tangled roots will naturally separate as you work, and you can gently tease them apart with your fingers without snapping them. If you are still worried about the mess, you can use a soft, dry brush to sweep away excess soil",
